In while and for loops, the condition is checked before every iteration. If variables used in the condition change inside the loop, that change affects whether the loop continues.let x = 0;

while (x < 3) {
    console.log(x);
    x++;
}

The condition is not checked only once. It is checked every time.

When JavaScript executes a for...of loop, it requests an iterator from the iterable object and repeatedly asks for the next value. Conceptually, the process looks like this:const arr = ["a", "b", "c"];
const iterator = arr[Symbol.iterator]();

console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: "a", done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: "b", done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: "c", done: false }
console.log(iterator.next()); // { value: undefined, done: true }

You do not need to write this manually in an introductory course, but it explains why for...of works across many different kinds of data.

let x = 0;

while (x = 5) {
    console.log(x);
}

This is wrong. The expression x = 5 assigns 5 to x, and the value 5 is truthy, so the loop never ends.

Correct version:while (x === 5) {
    console.log(x);
}

These happen when a loop runs one time too many or one time too few.for (let i = 1; i < 5; i++) {
    console.log(i);
}

This prints 1, 2, 3, 4. It does not print 5.

Already discussed, but worth repeating because it causes endless confusion.const arr = ["x", "y", "z"];

for (const item in arr) {
    console.log(item); // indexes, not values
}

Consider:const nums = [1, 2, 3, 4];

for (let i = 0; i < nums.length; i++) {
    nums.pop();
}

This loop changes the array while also depending on its length. That can produce surprising behavior and skipped elements.

A for loop can use break and continue.for (const n of [1, 2, 3, 4]) {
    if (n === 3) break;
    console.log(n);
}

But forEach() does not support break in the same way.[1, 2, 3, 4].forEach(n => {
    console.log(n);
    // cannot use break here
});

If you need early termination, a regular loop is often better.

Repetition is controlled by loop constructs.let total = 0;
for (let i = 1; i <= 4; i++) {
